Local kennel violator of Humane Society of America's Puppy Mills list

by Taylor Anderson

Sat, May 7th 2016 at 9:29 PM
Updated Sat, May 7th 2016 at 10:56 AM
Missouri has more than 30 puppy mills that are repeat offenders, according to the Humane Society of the United States.

Edina, MO. — Americans love dogs, but the Humane Society of the United States says several million puppies are raised in horrible conditions.

The organization says tiny wire cages hold sick and injured dogs living in filth.

According to the release of the 2016 Horrible Hundred Puppy Mills by the Humane Society of the United States, these are just a few of the common conditions its cites in this industry.

"They can keep a mother dog in a cage only 6 inches longer than her body for her entire life without her ever being able to put a paw on grass, and we've petitioned the USDA to significantly increase those standards, " Humane Society of the United States Senior Director of 'Stop Puppy Mills Campaign' John Goodwin said.

More than half of the puppy mills exposed in the report are repeated offenders.

While regulations right now are minimal, the HSUS cites dozens of violators including Rabbit Ridge Kennel in Edina, Missouri.

"There are also some regions where we see that the violation that would be taken more seriously by inspector in different part of the country is instead reported as a minor violation and that sort of inconsistency isn't helping the enforcement system.," Goodwin said.

The HSUS says Rabbit Ridge Kennel has violated the Animal Welfare Act since 1996.

The complaint filed by the Animal and Plant Health inspection service to the U.S Department of Agriculture cites more than dozens of dogs with a variety of health problems.

The HSUS wants to bring attention to kennels that may not ever meet federal standards.

"We're urging state legislators to pass laws that raise their own standards and also put restrictions on commercial pet industry so they can't sell dogs from puppy mills." Goodwin said.

KHQA reached out to the Rabbit Ridge Kennel but it did not comment on this report.
